All Implemented Interfaces:
Pipe<I,I>, Node, Sink<I>, Source<I>, MetaDataManageable<Object,Object>, MetaDataProvider<CompositeMetaData<Object,Object>>
public class Sampler<I>
extends Filter<I>

A Sampler is a specialization of the class Filter, which guarantees that each element of the input stream takes place in the output stream with the same probability p. This processing guarantees that the output stream represents a sample of the input stream.
An instance of the class ContinuousRandomNumber is used to generate uniformly distributed continuous random numbers within range [0, 1]. The parameter p denotes the Bernoulli probability. For each incoming element a new random number is generated and compared with the specified Bernoulli probability. If the random number is lower than p the element is transferred, otherwise discarded.

Example usage (1): 

        Sampler sampler = new Sampler(
                new Enumerator(10000, 0),
                new ContinuousRandomNumber(new JavaContinuousRandomWrapper()),
                0.5d // Bernoulli probability
        );
        new Tester(sampler);

Since:
1.1
See Also:
ContinuousRandomNumber, Predicate

Sampler

public Sampler(Source<? extends I> source,
               int sourceID,
               ContinuousRandomNumber crn,
               double p)
Creates a new Sampler as an internal component of a query graph.
The subscription to the specified source is fulfilled immediately.

Parameters:
source - This pipe gets subscribed to the specified source.
ID - This pipe uses the given ID for subscription.
crn - ContinuousRandomNumber generator.
p - Bernoulli probability. For each incoming element a new random number is generated and compared with the specified Bernoulli probability. If the random number is lower than p the element is transferred, otherwise discarded.
